    {
        "content": "<p>An alternative way to proceed for this proof:  To prove the goal <code>t ∈ F ∧ t ∈ Gᶜ</code>, you have to prove both <code>t ∈ F</code> and <code>t ∈ Gᶜ</code>.  The first is easy, because you have it as an assumption.  I would prove the second by contradiction: assume <code>t ∈ G</code> and then use your assumption <code>right</code> to get a contradiction.  (Note that <code>∀ t ∈ G, x ∉ t</code> is shorthand for <code>∀ t, t ∈ G → x ∉ t</code>.)</p>",
        "id": 451395623,
